fix_rag:
To comply with WCAG standards, the `<img>` element should have an `alt` attribute that describes the image's function or content. This is important for users who rely on screen readers to understand the content of the page. Here's the corrected HTML:

```html
<img class="rewardsIcon" 
     style="height: 20px !important;
            width: 20px !important;
            position: absolute;
            left: -25px;
            top: -1px;
            max-width: 20px;
            max-height: 20px;" 
     src="https://www.arabinstruments.com/static/frontend/Codazon/unlimited_sport/en_US/Mirasvit_Rewards/images/icon.png"
     alt="Rewards icon">
```

What was changed:

1. Added `alt="Rewards icon"` to the `<img>` tag. The `alt` attribute provides a text alternative for the image, which is read by screen readers. This text should describe the purpose of the image or the action it represents if it's an interactive element. In this case, "Rewards icon" is a simple description of the image's content. If the image is purely decorative and provides no content or functional information, you could use `alt=""` to let screen readers know that the image can be ignored.

Remember that the `alt` text should be chosen carefully to convey the right information to users who cannot see the image. If the image is part of a link or a button, the `alt` text should describe the action that will be taken when the user interacts with it, such as "View rewards details" or "Open rewards page".

fix_cot:
The accessibility rule violation `aria-valid-attr-value` refers to the use of ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) attributes in a way that does not conform to the values expected for those attributes. In the provided HTML snippet, the `aria-describedby` attribute is used. This attribute is intended to provide an accessible description for an element, where the value of the attribute should be the ID of another element on the page that provides the description.

In the given snippet, `aria-describedby="gallery-1-43285"` is used, but without the corresponding element with the ID `gallery-1-43285` present in the HTML, it does not point to a valid ID. This means that assistive technologies, like screen readers, will not be able to find the element that is supposed to describe the image, which violates the WCAG 2.2 guideline for providing descriptive labels for interactive elements.

To correct this, you would need to ensure that there is an element with the ID `gallery-1-43285` that contains a description of the image. Here's how you might correct the HTML:

```html
<img width="120" height="120" src="https://www.avpgalaxy.net/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2021/11/Screenshot_20211112-114018_Gallery-120x120.jpg" class="attachment-thumbnail size-thumbnail" alt="Description of the image content" decoding="async" loading="lazy" aria-describedby="image-description">

<div id="image-description" class="visually-hidden">
  A detailed description of the image for screen reader users.
</div>
```

In this corrected version, I've done the following:

1. Provided an `alt` attribute with a brief description of the image. This is essential for users who cannot see the image. The `alt` text should succinctly describe the image's content or function.
2. Added a `div` element with the ID `image-description` that contains a more detailed description of the image. This is what the `aria-describedby` attribute now points to.
3. I've used a class `visually-hidden` (which you would need to define in your CSS) to ensure that the description is not visible on the screen but is still accessible to screen readers. This is a common technique for providing additional information to assistive technologies without affecting the visual design of the page.

Here's an example of what the CSS for the `visually-hidden` class might look like:

```css
.visually-hidden {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px;
  height: 1px;
  margin: -1px;
  padding: 0;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
  border: 0;
}
```

This CSS effectively removes the element from the visual flow of the page without hiding it from screen readers.
